pr_body:
This is an attempt to get set up for OpenWrt builds for GSoC 2023.

The code and comments are mostly unnecessary (noop) at the moment and the plan is to work on them to get a clean setup working. Currently I'd like to know if the code design is accurate. For example, is running `make download` a reasonable approach to getting build dependencies installed? (It is the official way to do this under OpenWrt, and does not compile anything, only downloads files.)

I saw https://github.com/openSUSE/obs-build/blob/master/Build/SimpleJSON.pm but wasn't sure if that would work, and couldn't verify whether https://metacpan.org/dist/JSON was preinstalled.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 6, 15, 40, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ndren', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1219885997, 'comment_body': 'That makes sense, I will remove this (it turns out to be unnecessary). This also means that I cannot do git clones, but this basically means I will need to do a fake `git clone` from directory (`git clone SOURCEDIR TARGETDIR` style)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 6, 15, 41, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ndren', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1219890363, 'comment_body': 'Thanks, let me know if this works.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 6, 15, 44, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ndren', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1219892331, 'comment_body': 'The nice part about this method is that it keeps yaml parsing available if someone (or something, e.g. a buildsystem) prefers YAML.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 6, 15, 45, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ndren', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1219919375, 'comment_body': 'I am still wondering what I need to do about build-time dependencies (`make package/$NAME/download`), do I assume those are passed in as build inputs somehow?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 6, 16, 1, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ndren', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1219927949, 'comment_body': "I'm currently thinking of maybe having a list of git repos that are copied in that are comitted in the source build tree, though I'm not sure how that interacts with package/$NAME/download. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 6, 16, 7, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ndren', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1219931400, 'comment_body': "I have a question -- do you know if I'm able to use https://github.com/openSUSE/obs-build/blob/master/PBuild/RemoteAssets.pm before building?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 6, 16, 9, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ndren', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1287245901, 'comment_body': 'depends, pbuild is executing it always. 

For OBS scenarios the "download_asset" service would need to get enabled for that package or project.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 8, 14, 54, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adrianschroeter', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1287252254, 'comment_body': 'regarding dependencies, you may define a default as     build-packages:openwrt     in Build.pm in %subst_defaults.

This would require these packages by default (but can be overwritten by the user). 

You may also define an openwrt config file where you define default repository/ies via RepoURL: tag

 ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 8, 14, 58, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adrianschroeter', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1287253607, 'comment_body': 'you are of course allowed to use/add your name here ;)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 8, 14, 59, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adrianschroeter', 'type': 'User'}]
